mediaNotes: Various calls from an immature male foraging on hackberries at close range. Towards the end of the cut a Cooper's Hawk makes a swipe at the bird, and it flies away giving cackling calls.

A composite of recordings of the same young male Eared Quetzal that vocalized in between foraging and consuming caterpillars (a number of them quite long!), which it sought in tall pines, live oaks, and junipers--usually high in the trees, but occasionally coming low along the creek. It lifts its tail with each high-pitched call. We recorded vocalizations from 5:27-7:09AM, by which time it was mostly silent, with longer intervals between calls. I shortened the intervals by combining a series of vocalizations separated by 1 second intervals. Background species include: American Robin, Western Wood-Pewee; House Wren; Black Phoebe, Acorn Woodpecker; White-breasted Nuthatch, & Hepatic Tanager. Recorded using a Fostex FR-2LE with a Sennheiser ME62 & Telinga Universal 22" parabola.

Male Eared Quetzal, giving very quiet contact calls, then louder calls of two different types--the upslurred squeal ending in a "chuck"; and then intermittent loud, harsh cackles. Interval shortened by 30 sec at 15" and again by 45sec at 1'20". He is calling intermittently and flutter-grabbing wild grapes from a fruiting vine right beside the trail. Background includes: Mexican Jay, Hammond's Flycatcher. Recorded using a Fostex FR-2LE with a Sennheiser ME62 & Telinga Universal 22" parabola.

Spontaneous songs of a male Eared Quetzal as it moves up and down a stream valley en route to Cinco Millas, Santuario Madera. It flies high, from tree to tree, singing intermittently, as a second more distant, quetzal is sometimes heard in the background. I’ve combined several cuts of the same bird(s). Other background sounds include: distant Steller’s Jays, Thick-billed Parrots, N. Flicker (Red-shafted), a Brown Creeper, and an intermittent chainsaw in the distance. Recorded using a Fostex FR-2LE with a Sennheiser ME62 & Telinga Universal 22" parabola. Recordings after ca. 4' would probably qualify as 4-star.

An Eared Quetzal is calling in the canyon below our cabana at the Cabanas San Lorenzo, where running water is in the background. These are two successive cuts of the same bird, in the end flying farther away. (There were two birds, but one much farther away.) Recorded using a Fostex FR-2LE with a Sennheiser ME62 & Telinga Universal 22" parabola.

mediaNotes: Four cuts of song (and a call or two) of Eared Quetzals at dawn, in the stakeout area of Cave Creek Canyon just below the bridge below the SWRS, ca. 1600m. Starting at 6:00AM, when it was still too dark to see, a bird that had roosted in a big Alligator Juniper right by the road started singing--and was answered by a distant song. The close bird proved to be an immature male, and unless females sing (do they?), the distant song may be coming from a second male. (Some observers have reported seeing 3 birds, and one can sometimes hear a distant second song while a close pair is together.) As it got lighter, the close male began to move down the road with a female, which gives calls, as they move and then feed together on small fruits. These recordings were made between 6:00 and 6:15AM. Background includes: a Belted Kingfisher calling from near the creek just downstream from the bridge (most cuts), Brown Creeper (2nd cut); Northern Flicker (3rd cut); and some noise from vehicles and cameras.

Squee-chuck call, made by the male bird once it returned to it's perch after foraging a berry from a vine that looked like grape. The bird would give this call after it landed, lifting its tail up on squee and throwing it down on chuck. I think it's possible that the birds used this as a contact call as well. Sometimes the female would call like this and the male would go flying off into the bushes to find her. Incredible bird. Nathan Pieplow has better recordings.

"Chuckle" call from a male eared quetzal as it sallied out and grabbed what looked like a grape. Call was given as it returned to the perch. Bird would give a squeee-chuck call once it landed on the perch again, and while doing so, it would raise it's tail with squee, and lower it with chuck. Super cool to see and hear these birds.
